{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478610","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478610"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:34+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:13:34+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17526"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17526","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17526"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.3,0.13,0.22,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10216"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105732"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10216","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10216"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17526"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88198"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"8888"},{"type":"tags","id":"8891"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23898"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23899"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35617"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35921"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44006"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105732"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-day-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of eye discharge. He was born at term via normal vaginal delivery with no complications. His mother had limited antenatal care and did not receive routine screening tests during pregnancy. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There is watery to mucopurulent discharge from both eyes with mild conjunctival injection and lid swelling. The corneas appear clear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Topical erythromycin ointment only","Intramuscular ceftriaxone plus topical saline irrigation","Observation and regular eye cleaning","Oral azithromycin","Topical chloramphenicol only"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is highly suspicious for chlamydial ophthalmia neonatorum, caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E. The timing (5-14 days after birth), watery to mucopurulent discharge, and lack of maternal screening are classic features. While less severe than gonococcal conjunctivitis, prompt treatment is important to prevent complications including corneal damage and pneumonia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral azithromycin\u003C/strong\u003E is the current first-line treatment recommended by Australian therapeutic guidelines. A three-day course (20 mg/kg daily) not only treats the eye infection but also prevents the development of chlamydial pneumonia, which can occur in 10-20% of infected infants. All neonates with chlamydial conjunctivitis require referral to an ophthalmologist due to the risk of corneal complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical chloramphenicol\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate for chlamydial conjunctivitis, which requires systemic therapy to prevent both eye disease and pneumonia. There is no evidence that concomitant topical therapy improves outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntramuscular ceftriaxone plus topical saline irrigation\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for gonococcal conjunctivitis but is not effective against \u003Cem\u003EC. trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E. The later onset and less severe nature of the discharge make gonococcal infection less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical erythromycin\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient treatment. While erythromycin eye ointment is commonly used for prophylaxis at birth, systemic therapy is required once infection is established.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and regular eye cleaning\u003C/strong\u003E without antimicrobial therapy would risk progression of infection and development of pneumonia or corneal complications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing treatment, the birthing parent should be tested and treated for chlamydial infection. A test of cure using conjunctival and nasopharyngeal swab samples should be performed at least four weeks after completing treatment to ensure adequate therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cdiv class=\u0022table-container\u0022\u003E\u003Ctable border=\u00221\u0022 cellpadding=\u00225\u0022\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Cth\u003EFeature\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EGonococcal Conjunctivitis\u003C/th\u003E\u003Cth\u003EChlamydial Conjunctivitis\u003C/th\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETiming of onset\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E2-5 days after birth\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003E5-14 days after birth\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EDischarge\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ECopious purulent\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EWatery to mucopurulent\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ESeverity\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ESevere, risk of perforation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EMild to moderate\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETreatment of infant\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EIM ceftriaxone + irrigation\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EOral azithromycin for 3 days\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003Ctr\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ETreatment of parents\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003ECeftriaxone\u003C/td\u003E\u003Ctd\u003EAzithromycin\u003C/td\u003E\u003C/tr\u003E\u003C/table\u003E\u003C/div\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Neonatal chlamydial conjunctivitis typically presents 5-14 days after birth with watery to mucopurulent discharge.","Oral azithromycin is the current first-line treatment for neonatal chlamydial conjunctivitis and prevents pneumonia development.","All neonates with chlamydial conjunctivitis require ophthalmology referral due to risk of corneal complications."],"references":["Zikic A, Sch\u00fcnemann H, Wi T, Lincetto O, Broutet N, Santesso N. Treatment of Neonatal Chlamydial Conjunctivitis: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. J Pediatric Infect Dis Soc. 2018 Aug 17;7(3):e107-e115. doi: 10.1093/jpids/piy060. PMID: 30007329; PMCID: PMC6097578.","Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Conjunctivitis. In: Therapeutic Guidelines [digital]. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2024. Available at: https://app.tg.org.au.acs.hcn.com.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Antibiotic\u0026topicfile=bartonella-infections\u0026guidelinename=auto\u0026sectionId=c_ABG_Conjunctivitis_topic_5#c_ABG_Conjunctivitis_topic_5"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88198"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17526"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88198","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/88198"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-12T18:22:34+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-12T18:23:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10216"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105732"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"https://